{"cursor":"19074","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox language |name=Hindi |nativename= {{Unicode|MÄnak HindÄ«}}\n|image=Hindi.svg |imagesize= |imagecaption=The word \"Hindi\" in Devanagari script\n|pronunciation= |states=India Significant communities in South Africa, Nepal\n|speakers= 180 million |ref=e16 |date=1991 |speakers2= |familycolor=Indo-\nEuropean |fam2=Indo-Iranian |fam3=Indo-Aryan |fam4=Central zone |fam5=Western\nHindi |fam6=Hindustani |fam7=Khariboli\n|script=Devanagari (Brahmic) Hindi Braille |nation= |agency=Central Hindi\nDirectorate (India) The Central Hindi Directorate regulates the use of\nDevanagari script and Hindi spelling in India. Source:\n[http://hindinideshalaya.nic.in/hindi/introduction.html Central Hindi\nDirectorate: Introduction] |iso1=hi |iso2=hin |iso3=hin |linglist=hin-hin\n|lingua=59-AAF-qf |map=Hindustani map.png |mapcaption=Areas (red) where\nHindustani (Khariboli/Kauravi) is the native language |notice=Indic }}\n\n'Hindi', or more precisely 'Modern Standard Hindi', is a standardised and\nSanskritised register of the Hindustani language (Hindi-Urdu). Hindustani is the\nnative language of people living in Delhi, Haryana, Western Uttar Pradesh,\nBihar, northeastern Madhya Pradesh, and parts of eastern Rajasthan,\nand Hindi is one of the official languages of India. Colloquial Hindi is\nmutually intelligible with another register of Hindustani, (Modern Standard)\nUrdu, which is associated with the Muslim religion. The two varieties of\nHindustani are nearly identical in basic structure and grammar, and at a\ncolloquial level also in vocabulary and phonology. Mutual intelligibility\ndecreases in literary and specialised contexts, which rely on educated\nvocabulary drawn from different sources; Hindi drawing its specialised\nvocabulary from Sanskrit, whilst Urdu does so from Persian and Arabic.\n\nPeople who identify as native speakers of Hindi include not only speakers of\nHindustani who are Hindu, but also many speakers of related languages who\nconsider their speech to be a dialect of Hindi. In the 2001 Indian census, 258\nmillion people in India reported Hindi to be their native language; [http:/-\n/censusindia.gov.in/Census_Data_2001/Census_Data_Online/Language/Statement1.htm\nCensus of India] as of 2009, the best figure Ethnologue could find for\nspeakers of actual Hindustani Hindi (effectively Khariboli dialect less Urdu)\nwas a 1991 figure of 180 million. This makes Hindi\napproximately the sixth-largest language in the world.\n","linknr":800,"url":"Hindi_language","recorded":1376429170,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Hindi&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Hindi&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hindi","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Hindi_language&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Hindi_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Hindi.svg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/29/Hindi.svg/200px-Hindi.svg.png","/wiki/Devanagari_script","/wiki/Nepal","#cite_note-e16-1","/wiki/Language_family","/wiki/Indo-European_languages","/wiki/Indo-Iranian_l